## KEY LEARNINGS & BEST PRACTICES

### What Works Well
1. **Industry-Specific Approach:** Generic CRMs struggle to compete with industry-tailored features
2. **All-in-One Value Prop:** Consolidating 8-10 tools into one platform is compelling
3. **Emergency Services:** Unique differentiator that no competitor offers
4. **AI Automation:** Real-world workflows (prescription refills, emergency dispatch) resonate with users
5. **Transparent Pricing:** No hidden fees, no per-user charges, no revenue-based fees
6. **Free Trial:** 14 days with no credit card removes friction
7. **Affiliate Program:** Incentivizes word-of-mouth growth

### Technical Decisions
1. **FastAPI + React:** Modern, fast, scalable stack
2. **MongoDB:** Flexible schema for diverse data types
3. **JWT Auth:** Stateless, scalable authentication
4. **Modular Backend:** Separate routers per feature for maintainability
5. **Component Library:** Reusable UI components for consistency
6. **Environment Variables:** Easy configuration without code changes

### Challenges & Solutions
1. **Challenge:** Too many features can overwhelm new users
   **Solution:** Industry-specific onboarding that shows only relevant features

2. **Challenge:** Emergency services integration is complex
   **Solution:** Start with manual 911 dial, add API integration later

3. **Challenge:** AI costs can be high
   **Solution:** Use emergentintegrations for cost-effective access to multiple models

4. **Challenge:** Mobile experience is critical for field workers
   **Solution:** Prioritize mobile app development in Q2 2025

5. **Challenge:** Competition from established players (Salesforce, GHL)
   **Solution:** Focus on underserved industries and unique features (EPS, health monitoring)

